  "text": "Django's CSRF protection is implemented across three primary Python source files. The main middleware implementation is in django/middleware/csrf.py, which contains the CsrfViewMiddleware class that serves as the entry point for CSRF protection. The middleware's process_view method (line 414) orchestrates the token validation process. When processing a POST request, it calls the _check_token method (line 349), which retrieves the CSRF secret via _get_secret (line 221), validates the token format using _check_token_format (line 130), and compares the request token with the secret using _does_token_match (line 143). The _does_token_match function unmasks any masked tokens via _unmask_cipher_token (line 71) and then performs a timing-attack safe comparison using constant_time_compare from django/utils/crypto.py (line 65), which wraps Python's secrets.compare_digest. Additional security checks in process_view include origin verification via _origin_verified (line 271) and referer checking via _check_referer (line 297) for HTTPS requests. Token generation and rotation are handled by get_token (line 96) and rotate_token (line 117), which use _mask_cipher_secret (line 59) to create masked tokens from unmasked secrets. The process_response method (line 472) handles setting CSRF cookies or session values. The csrf_protect decorator in django/views/decorators/csrf.py (line 7) applies the same middleware-based protection to individual views, while requires_csrf_token (line 22) and ensure_csrf_cookie (line 42) provide related functionality. The csrf_exempt decorator (line 50) allows views to opt out of protection. The timing-attack prevention is critical and is implemented exclusively through the constant_time_compare function (django/utils/crypto.py:65) which delegates to secrets.compare_digest for all sensitive token comparisons."
}

